item.title: Democrat Woos Dairy Farmers to Keep Crucial Senate Seat
item.description: Sen. Tammy Baldwin had an unusual talent during her last election: convincing rural Wisconsin supporters of Republican Donald Trump to vote for her, too. This November, Senate Democrats need Baldwin to do it again.

item.title: Asia Manufacturing PMIs Show Some Weak Spots But Signal Growth
item.description: Asia’s latest factory activity data showed some loss of momentum midway through the third quarter, but a broad continuation of growth in output and orders.

item.title: Turkey Economy Shows Signs of Cooling
item.description: Turkish economic growth lost pace in the second quarter, a sign that restrictive monetary policy is cooling overheated activity that caused inflation to surge.

item.title: Atos Cuts Outlook on Softer Market as Clients Await Outcome of Rescue Plan
item.description: Atos warned of a worse performance than previously expected as clients cancel and delay contracts with the debt-ridden IT company, which now expects softer market conditions in the years ahead.

item.title: China EV Sales Rise on Government Subsidies, Inventory Buildup
item.description: Chinese electric-vehicle makers reported stronger sales and deliveries in August, thanks to Beijing’s expanded trade-in program and dealers building inventories for the September and October peak season.

item.title: China Property Slump Spurs Local Governments' Quest for Cash
item.description: China’s property crisis has hit local governments hard, drying up a key source of income as land sales crumble.

item.title: German Bund Yields Edge Higher; This Week's Data Might Provide Headwind
item.description: German Bunds should continue to be driven by Treasurys, potentially facing headwinds with this week’s U.S. data likely to stabilize rather than to wave recession flags, Commerzbank Research said.

item.title: Sanofi Multiple Sclerosis Drug Delays Disability Progression in Trial
item.description: A Sanofi experimental drug for multiple sclerosis delayed disability progression in a late-stage trial, but failed to reduce episodes of new or worsening symptoms compared to an existing treatment in other clinical studies.

item.title: American-Israeli Hersh Goldberg-Polin Among Six Hostages Shot Dead in Gaza
item.description: The Israeli military says the hostages were killed shortly before being found. Large protests erupt in Tel Aviv in favor of cease-fire deal.

item.title: Hardened Voter Pessimism About America's Trajectory Begins to Soften
item.description: WSJ poll finds that the share who say the U.S. is headed in the right direction is the highest since at least 2021.

item.title: The Last Days of Pokrovsk: Ukrainians Dig Trenches and Say Goodbye to Their City as Russians Close In
item.description: The mining town on the eastern front is preparing for impending destruction by Moscow’s troops, now just miles away.

item.title: China Caixin Manufacturing PMI Signals Improvement
item.description: A private gauge of China’s manufacturing activity returned to growth in August, contrasting with the official reading to paint a mixed picture of the sector.

item.title: Australian House Prices Extend Rise But Momentum Fades
item.description: Australian house prices posted their 19th consecutive monthly gain in August offering little hope the cost of mortgage borrowing will fall in the near term.

item.title: Australian Property Advertiser REA Mulls Offer for U.K.'s Rightmove
item.description: REA Group is considering a cash-and-share offer for U.K. counterpart Rightmove, citing what it called a transformational opportunity to create a $25 billion real estate advertiser.

item.title: Gold Futures Flat as Market Positions Itself for U.S. Economic Data
item.description: Gold futures were broadly flat, holding close to their all-time record high, as investors looked ahead to some critical U.S. economic data this week.

item.title: Oil Slips on Chinese Demand Concerns, OPEC+ Output Plan Expectations
item.description: Oil prices edged lower on persistent concerns over China’s demand outlook and growing expectations that OPEC and its allies will gradually increase supply starting from October.

item.title: A Home in This Kansas City Suburb Can Cost Millions. Just Ask Travis Kelce.
item.description: Leawood, where the tight end paid $5.5 million for a 11,631-square-foot spread, has the priciest residential real estate in all of Kansas.

item.title: Behind Matthew Perry's Deadly Trade With L.A.'s 'Ketamine Queen'
item.description: Prosecutors allege an M.B.A. graduate from an affluent Los Angeles suburb was the drug dealer at the center of the city’s ketamine craze.
